    {
        "content": "<p>Doing so implies that there will only be allocation failure but nothing else.</p>",
        "id": 300693105,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1664141925
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It also (sort of) breaks encapsulation because it requires all allocation to performed upfront before initialisation (IIUC). This wouldn't work if the allocation is under FFI, for example. An easy userspace example would be <code>pthread_mutex_init</code> that could return error.</p>",
        "id": 300693459,
        "sender_full_name": "Gary Guo",
        "timestamp": 1664142271
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>here is my newest blog post going over the design journey of my library: <a href=\"https://y86-dev.github.io/blog/safe-pinned-initialization/in-place.html\">https://y86-dev.github.io/blog/safe-pinned-initialization/in-place.html</a></p>\n<p>It also touches on ways of turning it into a language feature and will be the basis of a future RFC.</p>",
        "id": 302091207,
        "sender_full_name": "Benno Lossin",
        "timestamp": 1664812144
    }
]